**Props** (short for "properties") are how you pass data from a parent component to a child component.

Think of props like **function arguments** for components:

```javascript
// Function with argument
function greet(name) {
  return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}

// Component with prop
function Greeting({ name }) {
  return <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;
}
```

**Key facts about props:**
- Props are **read-only** - children can't modify them
- Data flows **one way**: parent → child
- Any JavaScript value can be a prop (strings, numbers, objects, functions)
- Props make components **reusable** with different data

// Parent component passes props
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Greeting name="Alice" />
      <Greeting name="Bob" />
      <Greeting name="Charlie" />
    </div>
  );
}

// Child component receives props
function Greeting(props) {
  return <h1>Hello, {props.name}!</h1>;
}

// Result: Three greetings with different names!

**Never modify props inside a component!**

```javascript
// ❌ WRONG - Don't do this!
function Counter(props) {
  props.count = props.count + 1; // Error!
}

// ✅ CORRECT - Use state instead
function Counter({ count }) {
  const [newCount, setCount] = useState(count);
}
```

Props flow downward. If a child needs to change data, it requests the parent to do it (we'll learn how later with callbacks!).

// Pass multiple props
function App() {
  return (
    <UserCard 
      name="Sarah Johnson"
      age={28}
      email="sarah@example.com"
      isActive={true}
      skills={["React", "JavaScript", "CSS"]}
    />
  );
}

// Receive all props
function UserCard(props) {
  return (
    <div className="card">
      <h2>{props.name}</h2>
      <p>Age: {props.age}</p>
      <p>Email: {props.email}</p>
      <p>Status: {props.isActive ? 'Active' : 'Inactive'}</p>
      <ul>
        {props.skills.map(skill => (
          <li key={skill}>{skill}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}

## Dynamic Props with Curly Braces

You can use any JavaScript expression inside `{}`:

```javascript
const firstName = "Alice";
const lastName = "Smith";
const age = 25;

// String concatenation
<User fullName={firstName + " " + lastName} />

// Template literals
<User fullName={`${firstName} ${lastName}`} />

// Math operations
<Birthday age={age + 1} />

// Function calls
<Display time={getCurrentTime()} />

// Conditional values
<Button disabled={!isLoggedIn} />

// Ternary operator
<Status color={isActive ? "green" : "red"} />
```

**Remember:** Use `{}` for any non-string value or expression!

